{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17480863","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17480863"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T23:52:58+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T23:52:58+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"119"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"119","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/119"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.09,0.03,0.02,0.84,0.02]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"119"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77124"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"119","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/119"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"119"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62631"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"7"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"185"},{"type":"tags","id":"1177"},{"type":"tags","id":"2375"},{"type":"tags","id":"2436"},{"type":"tags","id":"11010"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4200"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9228"},{"type":"contributions","id":"9607"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77124","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/77124"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 56-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a six-month history of steadily progressive fatigue, difficulty concentrating, numbness in her feet, and a tendency to trip. She has a medical history of hypothyroidism treated with thyroxine. She does not take any other regular medications. She eats a balanced diet and drinks one to two glasses of wine most nights.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, she appears tired. Her vital signs are within normal limits. She has pale conjunctivae and a smooth, red tongue. Neurological examination reveals reduced vibration and position sense in all limbs. Her full blood count shows macrocytic anaemia with hypersegmented neutrophils on blood film. Her renal and liver function tests are normal.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial investigation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Intrinsic factor antibodies","Lumbar puncture for oligoclonal bands","Thyroid stimulating hormone","Serum vitamin B12","Red cell folate"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with classic features of vitamin B12 deficiency: macrocytic anaemia (with hypersegmented neutrophils), neurological symptoms (impaired position and vibration sense suggesting subacute combined degeneration), and glossitis. The presence of autoimmune thyroid disease raises the possibility of pernicious anaemia as the underlying cause.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESerum vitamin B12\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate initial test to confirm B12 deficiency. A level below 148 pmol/L is diagnostic with 95-97% sensitivity. Treatment can be initiated based on this result.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIntrinsic factor antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E testing would be appropriate after confirming B12 deficiency to investigate for pernicious anaemia, particularly given the concurrent autoimmune thyroid disease. However, this is not the initial diagnostic test.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELumbar puncture for oligoclonal bands\u003C/strong\u003E would be considered in the investigation of multiple sclerosis. While MS can cause similar neurological symptoms, it would not explain the haematological findings or glossitis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThyroid stimulating hormone\u003C/strong\u003E testing is not the priority here. While hypothyroidism can cause fatigue and macrocytic anaemia, it does not cause hypersegmented neutrophils or neurological symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERed cell folate\u003C/strong\u003E measurement is not necessary as the initial test. While folate deficiency can cause similar haematological findings, it does not cause the neurological manifestations seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Vitamin B12 deficiency classically presents with macrocytic anaemia and neurological symptoms including impaired position and vibration sense.","Initial investigation of suspected B12 deficiency should be serum B12 level, with intrinsic factor antibodies reserved for confirming pernicious anaemia.","The combination of autoimmune thyroid disease and B12 deficiency should raise suspicion for pernicious anaemia."],"references":["Langan R, Goodbred A. Vitamin B12 Deficiency: Recognition and Management. Am Fam Physician. 2017 Sep 15;96(6):384\u20139. Available at: https://www.aafp.org/pubs/afp/issues/2017/0915/p384.html"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62631"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"119"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"62631","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/62631"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-06T09:36:02+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-06T09:36:03+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"119"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"77124"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"7","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/7"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udde0","name":"Neurology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"r